ContentClassification.Comments: Study Data: Complete life tables of Hong Kong were first produced in 1971 when detailed death statistics by sex and age were available for the first time in Hong Kong. The life table begins at the birth of each member of a hypothetical cohort, and continues until all have died. the mortality level of a population prevailing at a specified period of time is employed in establishing the mortality rates of a life table. Methodology: Simplifying assumptions include that the cohort is "closed" against migration; its composition changes only as a result of deaths of its members and at each age, excepting the first year of life, deaths are evenly distributed between one birthday and the next. Probability of dying, qx, is derived from the central death rate ux. At age 0, deaths are not uniformly distributed between the first and the second birthdays but tend to concentrate in the first few months of life. Therefore, formulas modified thus qx derived for each of the years from the infant death statistics. No graduation was applied to the death data, dx, but smoothing techniques were introduced when computing the probabilities of dying, qx. For ages 1 to 9, the qx's were smoothed according to the modified exponential curve and, in some very odd cases, to the log linear curve. For ages 10 to 74, the qx's were graduated by the Beer's modified formula. The qx's for ages 75 to 100 were obtained on the basis of the assumption that ux , the force of mortality could be described by the Gompertz model. For ages above 75, force of mortality rates extrapolated then qx derived by reciprocal relation. Limiting age taken as 100. Data Transcription Errors: None. Data Certified: 03/2014
